<subSubSection pageId="98" pageNumber="99" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="98.[140,1108,835,1319]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,312,905,931]" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis box="[185,307,905,931]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
This recently described species is restricted to the isolated dune of San Luis Obispo County, 
<collectingRegion box="[383,501,941,967]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">California</collectingRegion>
. It is pale powdery sandy brownish gray and has a pale elongate orbicular spot. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Troubridge &amp; Mustelin" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[416,609,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sala">
<emphasis box="[416,609,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Psammopolia sala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs within the range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[926,1049,976,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis box="[926,942,977,1002]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[958,1049,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The biserrate antenna (bipectinate in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[518,642,1011,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis box="[518,534,1012,1037]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[551,642,1011,1037]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), can be used to identify males. Females are distinguished from all 
<taxonomicName box="[439,583,1047,1073]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[439,583,1047,1073]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Psammopolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a shorter ovipositor lobe (0.27× as long as the ductus bursae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Troubridge &amp; Mustelin" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[378,451,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sala">
<emphasis box="[378,394,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[410,451,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">sala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 0.40× in other species). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Troubridge &amp; Mustelin" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[741,934,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sala">
<emphasis box="[741,934,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">Psammopolia sala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar in appearance and structure to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[486,598,1117,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insolens">
<emphasis box="[486,502,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[516,598,1117,1143]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">insolens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from central 
<collectingRegion box="[749,867,1117,1143]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">California</collectingRegion>
. Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Troubridge &amp; Mustelin" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[979,1050,1117,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sala">
<emphasis box="[979,995,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1009,1050,1117,1143]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">sala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a smaller cucullus than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[414,529,1152,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insolens">
<emphasis box="[414,430,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[447,529,1152,1178]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">insolens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(0.7× valve width compared to 1.0× width for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insolens">
<emphasis box="[1084,1100,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[140,222,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="98" pageNumber="99">insolens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Th e length of the ovipositor described above distinguishes females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
